    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm helping my dad with some estate stuff and he's asking about durable power of attorney. can u explain what that actually is and how it's different from just a regular power of attorney?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A durable power of attorney (DPOA) is a legal document that gives your dad the authority to act on his behalf, but it includes a special clause that makes it \"durable\"—meaning it stays in effect even if he loses the ability to speak, if he gets sick, or if he passes away. Unlike a regular POA, which usually ends immediately upon the principal's death, a DPOA remains active during incapacity and continues until the principal dies or explicitly revokes it.\n\nIn the world of estate planning, a DPOA is often the most critical tool because it allows your dad to manage his finances and property without needing to be physically present or mentally capable. This is especially important for someone with dementia or other cognitive conditions, as it ensures his assets are protected and bills are paid while he is still unable to manage them himself.\n\nThink of a regular POA like a temporary babysitter who only works when you are home and awake. If you get sick or fall asleep, the babysitter stops working. A DPOA, however, is like a permanent, always-on babysitter who stays with you no matter what, ensuring your dad's affairs run smoothly even when he can't help himself.",
