      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The third thing you need to look out for is the **scope of authority** and the **duration** of the document. While a DPOA is durable, it is still a legal document that can be revoked by your dad, and it must be clearly defined so the agent knows exactly what they can and cannot do. If the agent has too much power, they might feel empowered to take risks that hurt your dad's assets.\n\nRegarding the fear of dishonesty or \"sneaky\" behavior, the DPOA itself is just a paper trail; it doesn't stop a thief from stealing. To protect the money, you need to combine the DPOA with a **trust** or a **bank account** that the agent cannot touch without your dad's signature. Think of the DPOA as the \"keys to the house\" and the trust as the \"locked safe.\" Even if the agent has the keys, they can't open the safe without your dad's permission.\n\nAnother crucial step is to set up a **revocation clause** in the DPOA. This ensures that if your dad ever loses his mind or decides he wants to stop the agent from acting, he can simply sign a new document to cancel",
